  "response_text": "In black and white, the commercial opens on a close view of Soda Burst packages lined up on a shelf, as if in a store freezer or home freezer compartment. Two hands reach in from either side and handle rectangular cartons marked “SODABURST” and “2 instant ice cream sodas.” The Birdseye bird logo appears near the bottom of the packages. One carton is labeled “PINEAPPLE,” while another darker carton appears to be a chocolate variety, with pictures of tall soda glasses topped with ice cream and foam. The hands slide the boxes forward and lift one out.\n\nA carton is tilted open, and an individual cylindrical frozen serving is removed. The cylinder is wrapped in a light paper sleeve decorated with repeating small dark Birdseye bird shapes. Behind it, a Soda Burst box remains standing, again showing the “SODABURST” name and “2 instant ice cream sodas.” The wrapped cylinder is placed upside down into a tall drinking glass. A hand presses on the top of the container, then lifts the sleeve away, leaving the contents in the glass: a dark soda base with a pale scoop of ice cream sitting on top.\n\nA faucet spout moves over the glass. Water pours onto the ice cream and dark syrup, and the mixture immediately begins to foam. Bubbles rise and swell around the scoop, forming a frothy cap that climbs to the rim. A hand briefly steadies or adjusts the ice cream as the foam grows. The drink now looks like a freshly made ice cream soda, with dark liquid below, a pale ice cream mound at the top, and a thick ring of fizz around the rim.\n\nSeveral finished sodas are displayed together on a tabletop. They are in tall clear glasses, each filled with dark or pale soda and topped with frothy ice cream. Striped paper straws and long-handled spoons stand upright in the glasses. The foamy tops vary in height, some bubbling over slightly, giving them a soda-fountain look.\n\nA smiling young girl, about elementary-school age, appears behind two tall sodas. She has light-colo